      "createdAt": "2026-04-16T03:31:53.577141+00:00",
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "James, please don't apologize. What you just did — being honest about something that felt hard to admit — that took real courage, and I'm genuinely glad you told me.\n\nI want to sit with that for a second, because I hear two things in your message: the physical concern about your foot, and something that sounds like guilt about not speaking up sooner. Both matter. The foot we can work with. And the fact that you *did* tell me, right now, is exactly what good coaching relationships are built on. That counts for a lot.\n\n---\n\nNow, I have to be straight with you about something important: **diagnosing what's happening with your foot and telling you how to treat it is outside what I can do as your coach.** That's not me being evasive — it's me genuinely not wanting to steer you wrong on something this significant. Plantar fasciitis that's worsening with continued running, to the point of stopping you mid-run, really needs a physiotherapist or sports medicine doctor to assess it properly. They can tell you what's actually going on and what treatment makes sense. That's the right next step, and it's an urgent one.\n\nWhat I *can* tell you is this: **your training plan is going on hold right now, with no pressure and no judgment.** Not as a consequence — as the right call for getting you back to running well.\n\n---\n\nOnce you've seen your physio and have updated guidance, I'll be right here. We built a solid foundation before this setback, and a return-to-run plan from where you are is absolutely workable. This isn't a wall — it's a detour.\n\n**One question before you go:** Do you have a physiotherapist you can contact, or would it help to talk through what to look for in finding a sports medicine professional?"
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_012a3EcBAa5kFzYsc1N1XDWW"
    }
  ],
